On 4/18/2013 1:23 AM, John Cowan wrote:
&gt;
&gt; moira_ob scripsit:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; The whole point of Quikscript
&gt; &gt; is that it is capable of reflecting local ways of speaking - be it
&gt; &gt; American, Australian, Standard English or whatever. It is a phonetic
&gt; &gt; alphabet and that assumes that it will be written as it is spoken.
&gt;
&gt; QS is *not* capable of representing every accent of English unless
&gt; more than one sound is represented by the same letter. For example,
&gt; &quot;can&quot; = &quot;be able&quot; does not sound the same in New York City as &quot;can&quot; =
&gt; &quot;metal container&quot;, but QS has no way to represent the difference.
&gt; Still less is QS able to represent every accent of English simultaneously,
&gt; as the IPA can do, unless more than one sound is represented by the
&gt; same letter across accents. For example, the vowel of &quot;goat&quot; is not
&gt; the same in North American accents as it is in RP, but QS has no way
&gt; to represent the difference. The same is true of the vowel of &quot;mouth&quot;
&gt; as pronounced in Australia and in the Northern Hemisphere, but again
&gt; QS can&#39;t tell the difference.
&gt;
&gt; To make things worse, writing in QS exactly as we speak will cause severe
&gt; problems with intelligibility across accent boundaries. If Alice from
&gt; London writes &lt;Fife, Eat, Fife&gt;, North Americans will not recognize this
&gt; as &quot;thief&quot;. If Bob from Philadelphia writes &lt;Deed, Ah, Loll&gt;, people
&gt; from outside North America will not recognize this as &quot;doll&quot;. If Charlie
&gt; from Edinburgh writes &lt;Tut, Ed, Roar, Mime&gt;, only people from Scotland
&gt; and Ireland and those who know traditional orthography will recognize
&gt; this as &quot;term&quot;. If David from New Zealand writes &lt;Sis, Ado, Ax&gt;, only
&gt; his countrymen will recognize this as &quot;six&quot;; all other anglophones will
&gt; take it to be &quot;sucks&quot;. (&quot;Australia sux, New Zealand nil.&quot;) Likewise,
&gt; Eve from California will bewilder most of us with her &lt;Kick, Eat,
&gt; Inkling&gt;, as the rest of us say &lt;Kick, If, Inkling&gt; for &quot;king&quot;.
&gt;
&gt; When Frank, a policeman from Chicago, writes that he searched every &lt;Bob,
&gt; Loll, Ash, Kick&gt; for guns, the rest of us may think this is racial
&gt; profiling, but Frank merely meant that he searched every &quot;block&quot;.
&gt; Greta from Newcastle-on-Tyne may write &lt;Kick, Wool, Deed&gt;, and people
&gt; outside the North of England will think she is writing &quot;could&quot; rather than
&gt; &quot;cud&quot;. When Henry from Cardiff, Princess Imogen of Britain, James from
&gt; Melbourne, and Kayla from Indianapolis write &lt;Deed, If, Win-win&gt;, &lt;Deed,
&gt; Yo-yo, Ooze&gt;, &lt;Judge, Ooze&gt;, and &lt;Deed, Ooze&gt; respectively, it will take
&gt; them some work to figure out that all these spellings represent the word
&gt; &quot;dew&quot;. I could go on for a *very* long time.
